description.plain:
M83 is a French electronic/shoegaze/pop band from Antibes, formed in 2001 by Anthony Gonzalez and Nicolas Fromageau. Gonzalez remains the primary member of the band after Fromageau’s departure after the release of their second album. The band is named after the spiral galaxy Messier 83, and its musical aesthetic is influenced by shoegaze in its extensive use of reverb effects and lyrics spoken softly over loud instrumentals, although M83’s songs employ considerably less guitar than most shoegaze bands.

After the release of the crossover smash hit “Midnight City” from their 2011 double album Hurry Up, We’re Dreaming, M83 gained massive mainstream recognition, and has continued to tour and make music for movies and television.

description.plain:
“Midnight City” is off of M83’s sixth, and critically acclaimed album Hurry Up, We’re Dreaming (Naive, 2011). The song’s catchiness quickly made it one of the most popular songs of the year, appearing on the top of many “Best of” lists. The song is a tribute to city life and the city itself, especially how it comes alive during the nighttime.

Anthony Gonzalez’s comment on the use of the saxophone:

Sometimes a song needs an element to be finished. You know that this element has been overused in the past and is considered clichéd or cheesy, but the song needs it. With this album, the whole idea was to do something and have no regrets.

The music video is a tribute to the movies Village of the Damned and Close Encounters of the Third Kind.

description.plain:
French electronic masterminds M83 are back on the music scene with “Do It, Try It”, the first single to be released from their upcoming album Junk.

On March 1, M83 frontman Anthony Gonzalez took to Annie Mac’s BBC Radio 1 show to premiere the song. On the show, Gonzalez said “Junk” was hard to make after the success of M83’s last album, Hurry Up, We’re Dreaming, which debuted and peaked at No. 15 on the Billboard 200 chart and No. 1 on the Top Dance/Electronic Albums chart.

“It’s difficult,” Gonzalez said on BBC Radio 1, “It was my most successful album and because of that, I didn’t feel any pressure because I just told myself, well, you had an amazing success with the previous album so now you can do whatever you wanna do, so just experiment and have fun with your music and just put it out.”

Ces grands arbres, les hommes que j'ai aimés. Ces oiseaux qui volent, au loin, mon père disparu
Mes souvenirs ne sont plus des souvenirs
Ils sont là, vivants, près de moi, ils dansent et m'enlacent, chantent et me sourient

Teen angst in itself is defined as the depression and anxiety a teenager feels.
This M83 song describes the downs that come with being a teenager, which in this case, leads to thoughts of depression (and self harm). The song includes a beautiful instrumental where the words are placed into music, describing the ups and downs of being a teenager, which could show teen angst in itself.

“Couleurs” is French for “Colours”, which is an anomaly in this album; although M83 is a French electronic group, all of the other song titles are in English.

This song is mainly instrumental and the instrumentation builds and builds. According to a commenter on SongMeanings, “This song just keeps building, and building…amazing. I can definitely see some of the party lifestyles in it as well–as if each person coming to a party played a small part in the song. Over the course of the song the party grows and all the dialog and events blend together”.

Oh oh oh oh oh ohohoh

Between your lips
